  "companies": [],
  "statement": "# Merge Two Sorted Lists\n\nTwo linked lists are already sorted in ascending order. Return one sorted list containing every node value from both lists.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: list1 = [-3,1,5], list2 = [-2,4,6]\nOutput: [-3,-2,1,4,5,6]\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: list1 = [], list2 = [0,9]\nOutput: [0,9]\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: list1 = [4], list2 = []\nOutput: [4]\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- The judge provides a `ListNode` class with `val` and `next` fields.\n- Node values fit in normal signed integer range.\n- The total number of nodes across one test case is kept small enough for local execution.",
  "editorial": "Use a dummy head and repeatedly attach the smaller current node. Once one list is empty, attach the remainder of the other list.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def mergeTwoLists(self, list1, list2):\n        dummy = ListNode(0)\n        tail = dummy\n        while list1 and list2:\n            if list1.val <= list2.val:\n                tail.next = list1\n                list1 = list1.next\n            else:\n                tail.next = list2\n                list2 = list2.next\n            tail = tail.next\n        tail.next = list1 or list2\n        return dummy.next\n```",
  "hints": [
    "A dummy node avoids special handling for the first output node.",
    "When one list finishes, the remaining nodes are already sorted."
  ],
  "starter_code": {
    "python": "class Solution:\n    def mergeTwoLists(self, list1, list2):\n        pass\n"
  },
  "entrypoint": {
    "class_name": "Solution",
    "method_name": "mergeTwoLists"
  },
  "checker": {
    "type": "exact"
  },
  "time_limit_ms": 2000,
